article.headline: Lakers win fifth of last seven games
article.linkText: Kobe, Lakers hold off injury-depleted Hornets
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Chucky Atkins was in a sour mood at halftime Sunday night. He wasn't alone. The Los Angeles Lakers trailed the injury-depleted New Orleans Hornets by one point, and Atkins hadn't attempted a shot from the floor or the foul line in 13 foul-plagued minutes. The second half was a different story. Atkins had 17 points, two assists and two steals, and the Lakers took command midway through the fourth quarter in beating the Hornets 89-76. "He was the catalyst that got us going," Lakers coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. "Tale of two halves," Atkins said. "I just wasn't able to get into the game (in the first half). The second half, I made an effort to look for my shots, be aggressive, make things happen. "When we play teams like that, we have to jump on them and let them know we mean business. We're going to make mistakes, but if we don't come out and play hard from the beginning, we're going to look bad." Atkins impressed former teammate Darrell Armstrong, who led the Hornets with 21 points and five assists. "Chucky's done well; I played with Chucky in Orlando, and that's why I'm really happy for him," Armstrong said. "He's getting an opportunity to start the game and finish the game. Now he's really learning how to be a pro. "He's making big shots for them, especially tonight. He just leaves it all out there. They needed a spark, and he brought it." Kobe Bryant led the Lakers with 20 points, six rebounds and seven assists, but didn't have one of his better games, shooting 7-of-20, committing seven turnovers and missing an uncontested dunk with about 15 seconds left in the third quarter. "When stuff like that happens, you know he's human," Atkins said. Bryant was able to smile about the missed dunk since the Lakers won. "I got up a little too high, my forearm hit the front of the rim, the ball hit the back of the rim," he explained. "My foot felt great. It's been a while since I jumped off one foot." Bryant was diagnosed earlier this month with plantar fasciitis in his left foot, and has sat out several practices. But he has played big minutes in just about every game. Lamar Odom had 14 points and 14 rebounds, and Caron Butler and Brian Cook scored 10 each for the Lakers (8-6), who won for the fifth time in seven games. Tomjanovich sighed as he studied the box score. "Well, it wasn't pretty, but very important win," he said. "I thought our defense was pretty good. And we needed it to win this game. "I did not like the way we started the game. I didn't like the approach we had. I said at halftime, `Do we have to experience a loss for this to really hit us?" David West equaled his career high with 15 points and also had eight rebounds for the Hornets, whose 1-11 record is the NBA's worst. Junior Harrington had season-high totals of 14 points and eight rebounds and P.J. Brown added 12 points and 11 rebounds for New Orleans. Lee Nailon, averaging 12.7 points, shot 1-of-14 for two points for the Hornets, who are playing without injured All-Stars Baron Davis and Jamaal Magloire. For the most part, the game was poorly played. The Lakers shot 40 percent and committed 18 turnovers. The Hornets shot 33.8 percent and turned the ball over 17 times. It was a different story at the foul line -- the Lakers went 21-of-22 and the Hornets were 19-of-22. Los Angeles made its first 17 free throws before Odom missed with 3:50 left. The Lakers put the game away by scoring seven straight points -- five by Atkins -- to give them an 83-70 lead with 4:51 remaining. They went ahead for good by scoring the last seven points of the third quarter for a 67-63 lead. The Hornets weren't closer than three after that.

Game notes
Davis has missed seven games because of an inflamed disk in his lower back. A team spokesman said there is no timetable for his return. ... Magloire broke his right ring finger at Phoenix on Friday night and will be examined Monday by a hand specialist in New Orleans. ... The Hornets also played without Alex Garcia, who has a strained right groin. ... Brown said that because of their slow start, the Hornets were discouraged even before Davis and Magloire got hurt. "You've got to move on," he said. "When we get our guys back, we get them back. Nobody's going to feel sorry for us." ... The Lakers play at Milwaukee and Chicago this week before returning to Staples Center, where they'll play 10 of their following 12 games including one against the Clippers as the road team. ... Bryant was hit with a technical foul late in the third quarter after being called for an offensive foul.
